{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_29","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '320,470p' src/quant/q8_0_dot.HC\"","aggregated_output":"\nI32 Q8_0DotRowBlocksQ16Checked(Q8_0Block *row_blocks, Q8_0Block *vec_blocks, I64 block_count, I64 *out_dot_q16)\n{\n    I64 total_dot_q16;\n    I32 status;\n\n    if (!row_blocks || !vec_blocks || !out_dot_q16)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_NULL_PTR;\n    if (block_count < 0)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_BAD_DST_LEN;\n\n    // Checked row helper for WS4 call-sites that require explicit overflow status.\n    // Semantics are intentionally identical to blockwise Q16 accumulation:\n    //   row_total = Sum( RoundQ16(block_dot_q32) )\n    // with the same I64 overflow guards used by checked matrix kernels.\n    total_dot_q16 = 0;\n    status = Q8_0DotProductBlocksQ16AccumulateChecked(row_blocks, vec_blocks, block_count, &total_dot_q16);\n    if (status != Q8_0_OK)\n        return status;\n\n    *out_dot_q16 = total_dot_q16;\n    return Q8_0_OK;\n}\n\nI32 Q8_0DotRowsQ16MatrixVector(Q8_0Block *matrix_blocks, I64 row_count, I64 row_stride_blocks, Q8_0Block *vec_blocks, I64 vec_block_count, I64 *out_rows_q16)\n{\n    I64 row_index;\n    I64 row_dot_q16;\n    Q8_0Block *row_ptr;\n    I32 status;\n\n    if (!matrix_blocks || !vec_blocks || !out_rows_q16)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_NULL_PTR;\n    if (row_count < 0 || row_stride_blocks < 0 || vec_block_count < 0)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_BAD_DST_LEN;\n\n    // Each row begins at:\n    //   matrix_blocks + row_index * row_stride_blocks\n    // and consumes vec_block_count contiguous blocks.\n    // Require stride >= active vector span so row windows are valid and auditable.\n    if (row_count > 0 && row_stride_blocks < vec_block_count)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_BAD_DST_LEN;\n\n    for (row_index = 0; row_index < row_count; ++row_index)\n    {\n        row_ptr = &matrix_blocks[row_index * row_stride_blocks];\n        status = Q8_0DotRowBlocksQ16(row_ptr, vec_blocks, vec_block_count, &row_dot_q16);\n        if (status != Q8_0_OK)\n            return status;\n\n        out_rows_q16[row_index] = row_dot_q16;\n    }\n\n    return Q8_0_OK;\n}\n\nI32 Q8_0DotRowsQ16MatrixVectorChecked(\n    Q8_0Block *matrix_blocks,\n    I64 matrix_block_capacity,\n    I64 row_count,\n    I64 row_stride_blocks,\n    Q8_0Block *vec_blocks,\n    I64 vec_block_capacity,\n    I64 vec_block_count,\n    I64 *out_rows_q16)\n{\n    I64 row_index;\n    I64 row_dot_q16;\n    I64 required_matrix_blocks;\n    I64 row_base;\n    Q8_0Block *row_ptr;\n    I32 status;\n\n    if (!matrix_blocks || !vec_blocks || !out_rows_q16)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_NULL_PTR;\n    if (matrix_block_capacity < 0 || vec_block_capacity < 0)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_BAD_DST_LEN;\n    if (row_count < 0 || row_stride_blocks < 0 || vec_block_count < 0)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_BAD_DST_LEN;\n\n    if (row_count > 0 && row_stride_blocks < vec_block_count)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_BAD_DST_LEN;\n    if (vec_block_count > vec_block_capacity)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_BAD_DST_LEN;\n\n    // Hard bounds for caller-provided matrix extent.\n    if (!Q8_0TryMulI64NonNeg(row_count, row_stride_blocks, &required_matrix_blocks))\n        return Q8_0_ERR_OVERFLOW;\n    if (required_matrix_blocks > matrix_block_capacity)\n        return Q8_0_ERR_BAD_DST_LEN;\n\n    for (row_index = 0; row_index < row_count; ++row_index)\n    {\n        if (!Q8_0TryMulI64NonNeg(row_index, row_stride_blocks, &row_base))\n            return Q8_0_ERR_OVERFLOW;\n\n        row_ptr = &matrix_blocks[row_base];\n        row_dot_q16 = 0;\n        status = Q8_0DotProductBlocksQ16AccumulateChecked(row_ptr, vec_blocks, vec_block_count, &row_dot_q16);\n        if (status != Q8_0_OK)\n            return status;\n\n        out_rows_q16[row_index] = row_dot_q16;\n    }\n\n    return Q8_0_OK;\n}\n\nI32 Q8_0_DotRowsQ16MatrixVectorChecked(\n    Q8_0Block *matrix_blocks,\n    I64 matrix_block_capacity,\n    I64 row_count,\n    I64 row_stride_blocks,\n    Q8_0Block *vec_blocks,\n    I64 vec_block_capacity,\n    I64 vec_block_count,\n    I64 *out_rows_q16)\n{\n    // Compatibility entry-point for callers using underscored mixed-kernel naming.\n    // Keep one checked implementation path and delegate here to avoid semantic drift.\n    return Q8_0DotRowsQ16MatrixVectorChecked(\n        matrix_blocks,\n        matrix_block_capacity,\n        row_count,\n        row_stride_blocks,\n        vec_blocks,\n        vec_block_capacity,\n        vec_block_count,\n        out_rows_q16);\n}\n\nI64 Q8_0DotQ32ToQ16(I64 dot_q32)\n{\n    return Q8_0RoundShiftRightSigned(dot_q32, 16);\n}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_30","type":"reasoning","text":"**Exploring IQ requirement tests**\n\nI'm thinking about including tests that assess row-base guard behavior, kind of similar to a required capacity overflow sentinel by injecting a custom function. Maybe it would be smarter to implement a harness directly against HC contract functions from a Python reference and incorporate dedicated tests. This would cover scenarios like negative capacity, overflow, and adversarial conditions. The goal is to ensure that if we hit huge values, the function recognizes an overflow. I could create a test specifically for the row base guards as well.\n**Designing arithmetic tests**\n\nI realize we shouldn't call with huge row counts. A better approach might be to create a small helper function called `checked_row_base_for_index` to replicate existing behavior, which can help test boundaries. While the IQ asks for a harness, I think we can still integrate helper-level tests. To avoid large allocations, I might modify the existing test files. For overflow tests, using small row counts and larger scales could simulate conditions effectively. Let’s create a new test file and import needed constants, then design specific tests around expected behaviors.\n**Examining overflow guard coverage**\n\nI'm noticing that the helper constructs use `out_rows=[0]*row_count`, which can lead to issues with huge row counts if they overflow before allocation. The key seems to be that when row_count is set to `Q8_0_I64_MAX` and stride is 2, it returns overflow before trying to allocate. For testing row-base overflow guards, I think I can create a local helper function that checks for multiplication overflow conditions. I'll assert that the guard trips at boundaries, ensuring proper coverage of guard requirements. This mathematical approach should prove effective!\n**Considering synthetic checks**\n\nI'm thinking about using a synthetic executor to test the row-base guard path directly by defining a local function called `simulate_checked_loop_with_limited_i64`. This would perform row-base checks with limited parameters. For example, setting `max_i64` to 31, `row_count` to 6, and `row_stride` to 7 shows how the overflow occurs at index 5, demonstrating the guard logic. While this isn't in the kernel function, it could work as a host-side harness. To avoid overcomplication, I might directly test the overflow status with notes on the row-base guard as a proof. Exploring adversarial vectors could be insightful too!\n**Planning deterministic tests and tasks**\n\nI'm designing a deterministic test based on previous results, focusing on block contributions to huge positive Q16 values. When we pack signed values, we can create scenarios where two blocks might overflow, and we can verify if the function properly returns that overflow. For robustness, I’ll include some random sign generation to check for manual sum overflows. \n\nI'll also ensure that the function prints a success message and update the MASTER_TASKS queue. After reviewing unchecked items, I'll derive new tasks from them, maintaining a focus on implementing HolyC wrappers for efficiency. This could lead to substantial developments in the upcoming tasks."}}
